\section*{DIMENSIONS IN ELECTROSTATIC SYSTEM}

Let us derive the dimensions of some practical units in electrostatic system of units interms of $\mathrm{L}, \mathrm{M}, \mathrm{T}$ and $\varepsilon$.
1. Charge (Q) : According to coulomb's law force between two charges $Q_{1}$ and $Q_{2}$ is given by,
$$\mathrm{F}=\frac{\mathrm{Q}_{1} \mathrm{Q}_{2}}{\varepsilon \mathrm{~d}^{2}}$$
where
$$\mathrm{d}=\text { Distance between the two charges }$$
$$\begin{array}{rlrl}
\therefore & {\left[\mathrm{MLT}^{-2}\right]} & =\frac{\left[\mathrm{Q}^{2}\right]}{[\varepsilon][\mathrm{L}]^{2}} \\
& & {[\mathrm{Q}]^{2}} & =\left[\mathrm{ML}^{3} \mathrm{~T}^{-2} \varepsilon\right] \\
& \therefore & {[\mathrm{Q}]} & =\left[\varepsilon^{\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{M}^{\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{~L}^{\frac{3}{2}} \mathrm{~T}^{-1}\right]
\end{array}$$
where $\varepsilon$ is the permitivity of a free space.
And vacuum is assume to be unity in such systems
2. Current (I) : It is the rate of flow of charge.
$$\begin{array}{ll}
\therefore & \mathrm{I}=\frac{\mathrm{Q}}{\mathrm{t}} \\
\therefore & {[\mathrm{I}]=\frac{\left[\varepsilon^{\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{M}^{\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{~L}^{\frac{3}{2}} \mathrm{~T}^{-1}\right]}{[\mathrm{T}] \mathrm{S}^{\frac{0}{0}}}=\left[\varepsilon^{\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{M}^{\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{~L}^{\frac{3}{2}} \mathrm{~T}^{-2}\right]}
\end{array}$$
3. Potential difference or e.m.f. (E) : It is the work done per unit charge.
$$\begin{aligned}
E & =\frac{W}{Q} \\
\therefore \quad[E] & =\frac{M L^{2} T^{-2}}{\left[\varepsilon^{\frac{1}{2}} M^{\frac{1}{2}} L^{\frac{3}{2}} \mathrm{~T}^{-1}\right]}=\left[\varepsilon^{-\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{M}^{\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{~L}^{\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{~T}^{-1}\right]
\end{aligned}$$
4. Capacitance (C) : It is the ratio of charge and the e.m.f.
$$\begin{aligned}
& C=\frac{Q}{E} \\
\therefore & {[C] }
\end{aligned}$$
5. Resistance ( R ) : It is ratio of e.m.f. and the current.
$$\begin{aligned}
R & =\frac{E}{I} \\
\therefore \quad[R] & =\frac{\left[\varepsilon^{-\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{M}^{\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{~L}^{\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{~T}^{-1}\right]}{\left[\varepsilon^{\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{M}^{\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{~L}^{\frac{3}{2}} \mathrm{~T}^{-2}\right]}=\left[\varepsilon^{-1} \mathrm{~L}^{-1} \mathrm{~T}\right]
\end{aligned}$$
6. Inductance (L) : It is the ratio of e.m.f. and the corresponding rate of change of current.
$$\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{L}=\frac{\mathrm{E}}{\mathrm{dI} / \mathrm{dt}} \\
& \therefore \quad \mathrm{~L}=\frac{[\mathrm{E}]}{\left\{\frac{[\mathrm{I}]}{[\mathrm{T}]}\right\}}=\frac{\left[\varepsilon^{-\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{M}^{\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{~L}^{\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{~T}^{-1}\right]}{\left[\varepsilon^{\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{M}^{\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{~L}^{\frac{3}{2}} \mathrm{~T}^{-2}\right]} \\
& {[\mathrm{T}] }
\end{aligned}$$

