\section*{Wien's Bridge}

Wien's bridge is an AC bridge having four arms, which are connected in the form of a rhombus or square shape. Amongtwo arms consist of a single resistor, one arm consists of a parallel combination of resistor and capacitor \& the other arm consists of a series combination of resistor and capacitor.

The AC detector and AC voltage source are also required in order to find the value of frequency. Hence, one of these two are placed in one diagonal of Wien's bridge and the other one is placed in other diagonal of Wien's bridge.

The circuit diagram of Wien's bridge is shown in the below figure.
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_05_01_b9c6c5644ff12c14cd75g-115.jpg?height=728&width=1194&top_left_y=891&top_left_x=124)

Let, $Z_{1}, Z_{2}, Z_{3}$ and $Z 4$ are the impedances of arms $D A, A B, C D$ and $B C$ respectively. The values of these impedances will be
$$\begin{gathered}
Z_{1}=R_{1}+\frac{1}{j \omega C_{1}} \\
\Rightarrow Z_{1}=\frac{1+j \omega R_{1} C_{1}}{j \omega C_{1}} \\
Z_{2}=R_{2} \\
Z_{3}=\frac{R_{3}\left(\frac{1}{j \omega C_{3}}\right)}{R_{3}+\frac{1}{j \omega C_{3}}} \\
\Rightarrow Z_{3}=\frac{R_{3}}{1+j \omega R_{3} C_{3}} \\
Z_{4}=R_{4}
\end{gathered}$$

Substitute these impedance values in the following balancing condition of AC bridge.
$$\begin{gathered}
Z_{1} Z_{4}=Z_{2} Z_{3} \\
\left(\frac{1+j \omega R_{1} C_{1}}{j \omega C_{1}}\right) R_{4}=R_{2}\left(\frac{R_{3}}{1+j \omega R_{3} C_{3}}\right) \\
\Rightarrow\left(1+j \omega R_{1} C_{1}\right)\left(1+j \omega R_{3} C_{3}\right) R_{4}=j \omega C_{1} R_{2} R_{3} \\
\Rightarrow\left(1+j \omega R_{3} C_{3}+j \omega R_{1} C_{1}-\omega^{2} R_{1} R_{3} C_{1} C_{3}\right) R_{4}=j \omega C_{1} R_{2} R_{3} \\
\Rightarrow R_{4}\left(\omega^{2} R_{1} R_{3} C_{1} C_{3}\right)+j \omega R_{4}\left(R_{3} C_{3}+R_{1} C_{1}\right)=j \omega C_{1} R_{2} R_{3}
\end{gathered}$$

Equate the respective real terms of above equation.
$$\begin{gathered}
R_{4}\left(1-\omega^{2} R_{1} R_{3} C_{1} C_{3}\right)=0 \\
\Rightarrow 1-\omega^{2} R_{1} R_{3} C_{1} C_{3}=0 \\
\Rightarrow 1=\omega^{2} R_{1} R_{3} C_{1} C_{3} \\
\omega=\frac{1}{\sqrt{R_{1} R_{3} C_{1} C_{3}}}
\end{gathered}$$

Substitute, $\omega=2 \pi f$ in above equation.
$$\begin{gathered}
\Rightarrow 2 \pi f=\frac{1}{\sqrt{R_{1} R_{3} C_{1} C_{3}}} \\
\quad \Rightarrow f=\frac{1}{2 \pi \sqrt{R_{1} R_{3} C_{1} C_{3}}}
\end{gathered}$$

We can find the value of frequency, $f$ of $A C$ voltage source $b y$ substituting the values of $R 1, R 3, C 1$ and $C 3$ in above equation. If $R 1=R 3=R$ and $G=C 3=C$, then we can find the value of frequency, $f$ of $A C$ voltage source by using the following formula.
$$f=\frac{1}{2 \pi R C}$$

